quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The if Statement [/h1]

Very often when you write code, you want to perform different actions based on different conditions.
You can do this by using[b] conditional statements[/b] in your code.

Use [b]if[/b] to specify a block of code that will be executed if a specified condition is true.[code format="js" ]if (condition) {
   statements
}[/code]
The statements will be executed only if the specified condition is [b]true[/b].

[b]Example: [/b] [code format="js" codeId="660"]var myNum1 = 7;
var myNum2 = 10;
[b]if [/b](myNum1 < myNum2) {
   alert("JavaScript is easy to learn.");
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2751" width="100%"]
[note]As seen in the picture above, the JavaScript [b]alert()[/b] method is used to generate a popup alert box that contains the information provided in parentheses.[/note]

[h1]The if Statement[/h1]

This is another example of a [b]false [/b]conditional statement.[code format="js" codeId="661"]var myNum1 = 7;
var myNum2 = 10;
if (myNum1 [b]>[/b] myNum2) {
   alert("JavaScript is easy to learn.");
}[/code]
As the condition evaluates to false, the alert statement is skipped and the program continues with the line after the if statement's closing curly brace.
[note]Note that [b]if[/b] is in lowercase letters. Uppercase letters (If or IF) will generate an error.[/note]
